?´xT<?php exit; ?>a:6:{s:10:"last_error";s:0:"";s:10:"last_query";s:179:"SELECT   wp_posts.* FROM wp_posts  WHERE 1=1  AND wp_posts.ID IN (59,2) AND wp_posts.post_type = 'page' AND ((wp_posts.post_status = 'publish'))  ORDER BY wp_posts.post_date DESC ";s:11:"last_result";a:2:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"59";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-01-15 16:54:33";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-01-15 19:54:33";s:12:"post_content";s:39:"[gallery ids="769,766,765,764,768,767"]";s:10:"post_title";s:9:"Portfolio";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"portfolio";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-24 21:14:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-25 01:14:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://tere.invisible.cl/?page_id=59";s:10:"menu_order";s:2:"10";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"page";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:1:"2";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-01-15 01:41:35";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-01-15 04:41:35";s:12:"post_content";s:4164:"<p dir="ltr">The diverse landscapes of Chile have been the setting for the majority of the projects of Teresa Moller Studio since its founding in 1990. Distinct palettes of plants and materials are utilized as project locations range from the Atacama Desert in the north to the Lakes Region of the south as well as from the Pacific Coast in the east to the Andes mountain range in the west. This diversity has developed a way of working in the studio that approaches each project by examining the valuable elements existing in the site along with the surrounding natural systems, local ecology, and architecture. Thus, every project is a direct and unique result of its environment. The work has an architectural base, a geometry that structures the landscape over which the vegetation interacts more freely. Her work is characterized by its simplicity and Teresa strongly believes that in that simplicity lies its force. This force unites nature with architecture and provides a point of interaction between humans and their surroundings. Evident eastern influences arise from the similarities existing between the various ecologies of the Pacific coastal landscape.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The studio works in the realms of residential, public urban space, commercial, institutional and agricultural settings with many built projects to date. The goal of the office is always to collaborate with the architects and clients, using each participantâ€™s strengths and knowledge to arrive at an integrated design solution that is both efficient and elegant.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Design and Approach</h2>
<p dir="ltr">The key to our design approach is to find the perfect equilibrium in meeting the clients brief and carefully observing the existing landscape in order to understand how to develop the design.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Teresa Moller has been working in the field for over the thirty years. The office consists of a small team that includes architects, landscape designers and horticulturists. We work on a large range of projects from private gardens, large residential estates to commercial and public projects.</p>
<p dir="ltr">For Tere carefully observing the existing landscape of the site is key to all of her designs and her work process. In her own words Â´Exploring the landscape in order to fully appreciate what is existing in the site, is always my first stepÂ´. This involves physically spending time in the site to fully understand its moods and changes throughout the day and if possible seasons. By dedicating this time on site before the drawing board means Tere achieves an amazing comprehension of the site, its surroundings, its history and itâ€™s potential.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Construction</h2>
<p dir="ltr">For the projects in Chile we have a construction team that builds the designs. We work closely with the architects involved throughout the whole construction stage. Our team deals with architectural landscape construction, irrigation, soil preparation and planting.</p>
<p dir="ltr">For international projects we provide the specific details in order for a local contractor can carry out the work.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Teresa works very closely with the construction team, re-accessing design decisions whilst on site.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Maintenance</h2>
<p dir="ltr">A crucial aspect to any design is the maintenance. From the studio we provide a service where, if the client wishes, trained horticulturists visit the garden or project on a regular basis to provide advice. Generally this is formalized with a written report. This way we can ensure that the design achieves the foreseen result.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">La Mariposa</h2>
In the gardens of the studio there is a garden shop selling everything from potted plants, to tools and organic fertilizers. It is here where the studio has fun with small scale garden delights; water gardens, stone sculptures, a small potted grove of magnolia trees and even a fine selection of crocery. This wonderful shop "La Mariposa" (spanish for butterfly), all pay homage to the work of the studio, whilst allowing shoppers to take home a little piece of simple and classic garden design.";s:10:"post_title";s:22:"Study of the Landscape";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:6:"studio";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-11-27 12:35:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-11-27 15:35:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:35:"http://tere.invisible.cl/?page_id=2";s:10:"menu_order";s:2:"20";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"page";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}}s:8:"col_info";a:23:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:2:"ID";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:2;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:1;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:11:"post_author";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:1;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:1;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:9:"post_date";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:19;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:0;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:8:"datetime";s:8:"unsigned";i:0;s:8:"ze